<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-10-11T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-10-11T21:00:00-05:00" n="555" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d555">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 Moscow/19: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Hamilton</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-10-11T22:00:00-04:00">October
                                    11, 1943—10 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>980. Your telegram No. 1587, Oct. 11, 10 a.m. There has been no
                            announcement that the Three-Power Conference is to be held in Moscow and
                            no announcement that the Secretary is heading our delegation. The
                            British Embassy had informed us that it had been jointly agreed with the
                            Soviet Government that no announcement would be made until the arrival
                            at Moscow of the British and American delegations. We concurred in this
                            arrangement and are therefore at a loss to understand the statements
                            published in the British Daily Bulletin.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>[<hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>]</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>